{"id":3812,"date":"2025-10-08T13:00:00","date_gmt":"2025-10-08T11:00:00","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/?p=3812"},"modified":"2025-10-09T08:40:20","modified_gmt":"2025-10-09T06:40:20","slug":"so-and-because","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/so-and-because\/","title":{"rendered":"How to say &#8220;so&#8221; and &#8220;because&#8221; in Japanese"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>Probably the simplest way to build more complex sentences in Japanese is to take two simple sentences and join them together to form one longer sentence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Just as in English, one of the most common situations where we would do this is when we want to explain <strong>the reason for doing something<\/strong> or to show <strong>cause and effect<\/strong>. That is, to say something like:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>I did Y, <strong>because<\/strong> X happened.<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here, the word &#8220;because&#8221; is joining two separate statements &#8211; &#8220;I did Y&#8221; and &#8220;X happened&#8221; &#8211; and in doing so, explains that one of these actions is the reason for the other one.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Another way to express the above sentence is like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>X happened, <strong>so<\/strong> I did Y.<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is the same information, but we&#8217;ve swapped the order of the statements and used &#8220;so&#8221; instead of &#8220;because&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In this article, we will see how we can use the particles <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> to connect two actions together in this way to effectively say &#8220;so&#8221; or because&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We&#8217;re also going to do this in both polite and informal Japanese, and we will see how the rules apply slightly differently in each case.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<!--more-->\n\n\n\n<div class=\"rw-toc\">\n<div class=\"rw-toc-title\">Table of Contents<\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#so-because\"><strong>Saying &#8220;so&#8221; and &#8220;because&#8221; in Japanese<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#kara\"><strong>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> to say &#8220;so&#8221; or &#8220;because&#8221;<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class='rw-sub-contents'><div><a href='#kara-action'>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with an action as the reason<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href='#kara-i-adjective'>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with an i-adjective as the reason<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href='#kara-na-adjective'>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with a na-adjective as the reason<\/a><\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#node\"><strong>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> to say \u201cso\u201d or &#8220;because&#8221;<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n<div class='rw-sub-contents'><div><a href='#node-action'>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> with an action as the reason<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href='#node-i-adjective'>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> with an i-adjective as the reason<\/a><\/div>\n<div><a href='#node-na-adjective'>Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> with a na-adjective as the reason<\/a><\/div><\/div>\n<div><a href=\"#key-takeaways\"><strong>Key Takeaways<\/strong><\/a><\/div>\n\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"so-because\">Saying &#8220;so&#8221; and &#8220;because&#8221; in Japanese<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>As mentioned above, in English we can use the words &#8220;so&#8221; or &#8220;because&#8221; (or similar words like &#8220;therefore&#8221;, &#8220;since&#8221;, &#8220;hence&#8221;, etc.) to join two statements together where one of the things described is the reason or cause for the other. That looks something like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"183\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/01-english-so-because-1024x183.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3827\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/01-english-so-because-1024x183.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/01-english-so-because-300x54.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/01-english-so-because-768x137.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/01-english-so-because-1536x275.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/01-english-so-because-2048x366.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In Japanese, the first alternative is effectively how this is always expressed. That is, usually:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong><em>The reason or cause is described first, and the action that was taken as a result is described second.<\/em><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In other words, reasons or cause and effect are typically expressed as:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>X happened, <strong>so<\/strong> I did Y.<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>It is still possible to describe the resulting action first and give the reason second, but when describing both in a single sentence, the reason or cause generally comes first.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The way we express this in Japanese is to describe the reason, followed by either <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> or <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, and then describe the resulting action, like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"267\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/02-kara-node-1024x267.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3828\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/02-kara-node-1024x267.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/02-kara-node-300x78.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/02-kara-node-768x200.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/02-kara-node-1536x400.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/02-kara-node-2048x533.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Now, this is a very simple, high-level view of how we do this and there are some differences between the two particles, which we will look at closely in a moment.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In simple terms, the differences between using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> are:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>How we connect them to the first clause (the part of the sentence describing the reason or cause). The rules are a little bit different for each.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>How they work in polite vs informal Japanese. If speaking politely, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> would generally be considered more polite than <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, but we can use both in either case.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>Let&#8217;s take a closer look at each of these now, starting with more straightforward option: <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"kara\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> to say &#8220;so&#8221; or &#8220;because&#8221;<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>We can use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> to effectively say \u201cso\u201d to join a reason with its result, or a cause with its effect.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To do this, we first say our reason, and we express this in just the same way as we would express anything else according to <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/japanese-sentence-structure\/\">our sentence model<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"428\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/05\/Japanese-sentence-structure-1024x428.png\" alt=\"Japanese sentence structure\" class=\"wp-image-1565\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/05\/Japanese-sentence-structure-1024x428.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/05\/Japanese-sentence-structure-300x126.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/05\/Japanese-sentence-structure-768x321.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/05\/Japanese-sentence-structure-1536x643.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/05\/Japanese-sentence-structure-2048x857.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>As always, we just have a topic, followed by some other information, and then the verb at the end.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Now, I usually refer to this [topic &#8211; other information &#8211; verb] structure as a model for <em>sentences<\/em>, but really, this is the structure of a <strong><em>clause<\/em><\/strong>. This is an important distinction because one sentence can have multiple clauses.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>A clause is essentially one complete idea, and it always has a main verb. A clause therefore always describes at least one action, even if that action isn&#8217;t a real &#8220;action&#8221;, but is just, for example, the act of \u201cbeing\u201d as described using <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/desu\/\">the special verb <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/a>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Simple sentences consist of just one clause, but if we want to say something like, &#8220;X happened, so I did Y&#8221;, we need two clauses. We need:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>One clause that says, &#8220;X happened&#8221;, then<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>A second clause that says, &#8220;I did Y&#8221;, plus<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Something in between these clauses to join them together<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>In this case, we want to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> to show that the action described in the first clause is the reason or cause of the second, so it looks like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"286\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/04-reason-kara-result-1024x286.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3829\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/04-reason-kara-result-1024x286.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/04-reason-kara-result-300x84.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/04-reason-kara-result-768x214.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/04-reason-kara-result-1536x428.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/04-reason-kara-result-2048x571.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-group rw-sidebar\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained\">\n<p>In this case, we are using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> to effectively say &#8220;so&#8221;, but this idea can be applied to many other situations too.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Another extremely common situation where we do this is when saying &#8220;but&#8221;. For example, if we want to say, \u201cI did X, but then Y happened,\u201d we can do that in much the same way as we are doing here. We would have one clause to describe the first thing, then a particle that means \u201cbut,\u201d and then another clause that contrasts with the first one.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In some cases, the sentence structure is like it is here, with two clauses joined by a particle. In other cases, the way we connect the two clauses is to actually conjugate the verb of the first clause into a different form.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We won&#8217;t go into that in more detail here as we&#8217;re only concerned with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> for now, but there are a number of ways we can string two or more clauses together to form longer, more complex sentences, and usually, each clause can, individually, be expressed using some variation of our general sentence model.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The way that we connect <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> to the verb is very simple. We simple <strong>place it immediately after the verb in the first clause<\/strong>. We don&#8217;t need to change either clause in any way.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Even better is that we can do this with both polite and informal Japanese, so whether the verbs are in the polite form or the informal form, we can place <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> immediately after the first clause&#8217;s verb.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>That said, it is important to be consistent, so <strong>the politeness level of the two verbs should be the same<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"377\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/05-politeness-match-kara-1024x377.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3830\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/05-politeness-match-kara-1024x377.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/05-politeness-match-kara-300x110.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/05-politeness-match-kara-768x283.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/05-politeness-match-kara-1536x566.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/05-politeness-match-kara-2048x754.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>If we want the whole sentence to be polite, then the main verb of each clause should be polite. If we are talking informally, both verbs should be informal, though it&#8217;s less of an issue if you use a polite verb in such cases.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To get a better handle on this, let&#8217;s see some examples using different types of &#8220;verbs&#8221; and different levels of politeness.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"kara-action\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with an action as the reason<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>We&#8217;ll start with an example where we have a regular action as the reason for another action, and we&#8217;ll start by expressing it in the polite form. First, here&#8217;s the sentence we&#8217;ll use in English:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>\u201cI will go to Japan next year, <strong>so<\/strong> I will study Japanese every day.\u201d<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We have a reason (planned trip to Japan), and an action that is explained by that reason (will study  Japanese every day), joined by the word &#8220;so&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In <strong>polite<\/strong> Japanese, this would be:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/06-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-polite-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3831\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/06-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-polite-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/06-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-polite-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/06-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-polite-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/06-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-polite-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/06-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-polite-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Polite)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Polite)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa rainen, nihon ni ikimasu kara, mainichi nihongo wo benky\u014d shimasu.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093\u3001 \u306b\u307b\u3093 \u306b \u3044\u304d\u307e\u3059 \u304b\u3089\u3001 \u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061 \u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054 \u3092 \u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046 \u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u6765\u5e74<rt>\u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001<ruby>\u65e5\u672c<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3059\u304b\u3089\u3001<ruby>\u6bce\u65e5<rt>\u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby><ruby>\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>As you can see, we first have one clause that says:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will go to Japan next year.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa rainen, nihon ni ikimasu.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093\u3001 \u306b\u307b\u3093 \u306b \u3044\u304d\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u6765\u5e74<rt>\u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001<ruby>\u65e5\u672c<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>We then have <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, which effectively means \u201cso,\u201d followed by the second part of the sentence:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will study Japanese every day.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">mainichi nihongo wo benky\u014d shimasu.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061 \u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054 \u3092 \u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046 \u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u6bce\u65e5<rt>\u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby><ruby>\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Independently, the first half of the sentence and the second half of the sentence just follow the same structure of every other simple Japanese sentence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>You&#8217;ll notice, however, that while first clause has a topic, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;watashi&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span>, the second clause does not.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is simply because it is implied. When we get to the second clause, we already know that we&#8217;re talking about \u201cme,\u201d so we don&#8217;t need to say <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;watashi wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u300d<\/span> again.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The person who will go to Japan and the person who will study is the same person, so there&#8217;s no need to repeat this information. In English we would, but that&#8217;s because in English we&#8217;re obligated to have a subject (in this case &#8220;I&#8221;) in every clause. In Japanese, however, information that is known or understood from context can simply be omitted.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>It&#8217;s also true that we don&#8217;t have to have any &#8220;other information&#8221;, either. In this case we do, but in Japanese, for a sentence to be considered complete, the only element it actually needs is a verb.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-sidebar\">For a better understanding of what the particle <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span> is actually for, and why we don&#8217;t always need it, see <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wa-vs-ga\/\">my article about the difference between <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;wa&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306f\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304c\u300d<\/span><\/a>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In terms of politeness, the verbs in the two clauses &#8211; <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ikimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;benky\u014d shimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span> &#8211; are both in the polite form, so of course the sentence as a whole is polite.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We could express the exact same thing informally by simply changing both of these verbs into the informal form: <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;iku&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;benky\u014d suru&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u308b\u300d<\/span><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This sentence expressed <strong>informally<\/strong> would therefore be:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/07-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-informal-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3832\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/07-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-informal-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/07-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-informal-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/07-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-informal-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/07-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-informal-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/07-go-japan-kara-study-japanese-informal-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa rainen, nihon ni iku kara, mainichi nihongo wo benky\u014d suru.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093\u3001 \u306b\u307b\u3093 \u306b \u3044\u304f \u304b\u3089\u3001 \u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061 \u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054 \u3092 \u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046 \u3059\u308b\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u6765\u5e74<rt>\u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001<ruby>\u65e5\u672c<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u304b\u3089\u3001<ruby>\u6bce\u65e5<rt>\u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby><ruby>\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u308b\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>All we&#8217;ve done is conjugate the verbs into the informal form, and nothing else needs to change. Whether speaking politely or informally, the way we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> is the same.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"kara-i-adjective\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with an i-adjective as the reason<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Let&#8217;s see an example now where the reason for something is described using an i-adjective:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>\u201cYour pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine.\u201d<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We can express this in <strong>informal Japanese<\/strong> like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/08-pants-dirty-put-in-laundy-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3833\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/08-pants-dirty-put-in-laundy-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/08-pants-dirty-put-in-laundy-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/08-pants-dirty-put-in-laundy-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/08-pants-dirty-put-in-laundy-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/08-pants-dirty-put-in-laundy-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">zubon wa kitanakatta kara, sentakuki ni ireta.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3 \u306f \u304d\u305f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f \u304b\u3089\u3001 \u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d \u306b \u3044\u308c\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u306f<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u304b\u3089\u3001<ruby>\u6d17\u6fef\u6a5f<rt>\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>As with the previous example, here we just have two clauses joined by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The main structural difference here is that this time, our &#8220;verb&#8221; in our first clause is an i-adjective in the past tense. Because it&#8217;s in the informal form, we don&#8217;t add <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span> on the end; the clause just ends with the adjective.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-sidebar\">See <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/desu\/\">my article about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span> <\/a>to understand why this works even though there doesn&#8217;t appear to be a &#8220;real&#8221; verb.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We then join that clause to the second clause using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>. Of course, the second clause is also in the informal form, ending with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ireta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u300d<\/span>, which is the informal past tense form of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;iremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cto put something in something\u201d.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We therefore have a sentence that starts with a reason:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The pants were dirty.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">zubon wa kitanakatta.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3 \u306f \u304d\u305f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u306f<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Then <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, then the action explained by that reason:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">(I) put (them) in the laundry machine.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">sentakuki ni ireta.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d \u306b \u3044\u308c\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u6d17\u6fef\u6a5f<rt>\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>We again don&#8217;t have a topic in this second clause even though the topic of the first clause (<span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;zubon&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u300d<\/span> meaning &#8220;pants&#8221;) is not the implied topic of the second clause. In the first part, we&#8217;re talking about \u201cthe pants,\u201d and in the second part, we&#8217;re talking about \u201cme,\u201d who&#8217;s putting them in the washing machine. The topics don&#8217;t have to match.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>How can this work? Because the context still makes it obvious that it was &#8220;I&#8221; who put the pants in the laundry machine. The topic tells us what we are talking about; it provides context. It does not necessarily describe the person doing the action.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>When we say, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;sentakuki ni ireta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6d17\u6fef\u6a5f<rt>\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u300d<\/span>, there is no mention of either the pants or that it is me who put them in the machine. Literally, it just means, &#8220;put (past tense) in the machine&#8221;.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>That it was me who did it is implied, since there&#8217;s nobody else that I&#8217;ve mentioned, and it&#8217;s also implied that the thing I put in the machine is the pants, since that information was introduced earlier.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>When we have implied information like this, in English, we fill those holes with pronouns &#8211; words like \u201cI\u201d and \u201cthem.\u201d<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In Japanese, we just remove those entirely, so the literal translation becomes, \u201cthe pants were dirty, so put in the washing machine.\u201d We don&#8217;t need to include words that refer to myself and the pants because both of these are already understood, and to include them would actually sound quite redundant and silly.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The natural thing to do is to omit them and just say, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;zubon wa kitanakatta kara, sentakuki ni ireta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u306f<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u304b\u3089\u3001<ruby>\u6d17\u6fef\u6a5f<rt>\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-group rw-sidebar\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained\">\n<p>I should add, too, that in many, maybe even most situations, it would be more natural to have <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;zubon&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u300d<\/span> as the subject in the first clause marked by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ga&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304c\u300d<\/span>, making it, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;zubon ga kitanakatta kara&#8230;&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u304c<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u304b\u3089&#8230;\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wa-vs-ga\/\">That choice<\/a> depends on the context, but I chose to use it as the topic here to highlight the independence of the two clauses, and what information is assumed from context.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"kara-na-adjective\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with a na-adjective as the reason<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Now let&#8217;s see an example where we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> after a clause that describes a reason using a na-adjective, again in <strong>informal<\/strong> Japanese:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/09-garbage-full-kara-put-outside-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3834\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/09-garbage-full-kara-put-outside-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/09-garbage-full-kara-put-outside-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/09-garbage-full-kara-put-outside-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/09-garbage-full-kara-put-outside-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/09-garbage-full-kara-put-outside-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai da kara, soto ni dasu yo.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u3060 \u304b\u3089\u3001 \u305d\u3068 \u306b \u3060\u3059 \u3088\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u3060\u304b\u3089\u3001<ruby>\u5916<rt>\u305d\u3068<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u3088\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Here, our reason is described by the na-adjective <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ippai&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u300d<\/span>, which means \u201cfull.\u201d The way we complete a clause ending in a na-adjective in the informal form is by adding <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span>. In the polite, we would use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span>, so the polite version of the first clause would be:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full. (Polite)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai desu.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u3067\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u3067\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>In the informal form, for na-adjectives like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ippai&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u300d<\/span>, we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span> instead:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai da.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u3060\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u3060\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Then, we just add <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> after this, followed by the second clause:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">(I) will put (it) outside.<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">soto ni dasu yo.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305d\u3068 \u306b \u3060\u3059 \u3088\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u5916<rt>\u305d\u3068<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u3088\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>As with the other examples, we don&#8217;t need to change anything else about the sentence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Once again, it is implied that it is \u201cI\u201d who will put the garbage outside, since nobody else is mentioned and we don&#8217;t have any other context.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We also know from the first part of the sentence that we&#8217;re talking about the garbage bin, so that must be the thing that I&#8217;m going to put outside.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We also have <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;yo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3088\u300d<\/span> at the end of the sentence because that&#8217;s just something that some people might say in this situation, perhaps as a way to emphasize that I&#8217;m going to do this now. We&#8217;re telling the person what we&#8217;re going to do, and that&#8217;s new information to them.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-sidebar\">For a more detailed explanation how and when to use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;yo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3088\u300d<\/span>, see <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/yo-and-ne\/\">my article about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;yo&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3088\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ne&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306d\u300d<\/span><\/a>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<p>As you can see from these examples, using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> is really quite easy. We start with a clause (which is essentially just a simple sentence) that describes the cause or reason for something, then add <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, and then add another clause that describes the effect or result of that cause or reason.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The two parts of the sentence are independent clauses, and we don&#8217;t need to do anything differently to them. We can use both in either the informal form or the polite form, as long as we&#8217;re consistent.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let&#8217;s now see how we can use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> in a similar way, but with some important differences.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"node\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> to say \u201cso\u201d or &#8220;because&#8221;<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Just like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, we can use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> to effectively say \u201cso\u201d, connecting a cause or reason to an effect or result.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The order in which we structure the sentence is the same as with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>. We have the cause or reason first, then <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, and then the effect or result, like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"232\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/10-reason-node-result-1024x232.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3835\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/10-reason-node-result-1024x232.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/10-reason-node-result-300x68.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/10-reason-node-result-768x174.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/10-reason-node-result-1536x348.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/10-reason-node-result-2048x464.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The big difference is in how we connect the first verb (or verb-equivalent) to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong>The clause before <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> is generally expressed in the informal form<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Perhaps the &#8220;plain form&#8221; is a better descriptor here, since this applies even in polite sentences (we&#8217;ll get to that soon), but we&#8217;ll stick with &#8220;informal form&#8221; for simplicity and consistency.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There is, however, an important exception:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong>For nouns and na-adjectives, the present\/future tense form is connected to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span> instead of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Let&#8217;s back up a bit.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Japanese sentences (or clauses) can end either with a regular verb, or with a noun or adjective combined with some variation of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span>. A very simple example that uses a noun and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span> in the <strong>polite<\/strong> form might be:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"183\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/11-kore-kuruma-desu-1024x183.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3836\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/11-kore-kuruma-desu-1024x183.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/11-kore-kuruma-desu-300x54.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/11-kore-kuruma-desu-768x137.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/11-kore-kuruma-desu-1536x275.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/11-kore-kuruma-desu-2048x366.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">This is a car. (Polite)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">This is a car. (Polite)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">kore wa kuruma desu.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3053\u308c \u306f \u304f\u308b\u307e \u3067\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3053\u308c\u306f<ruby>\u8eca<rt>\u304f\u308b\u307e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3067\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>In the <strong>informal<\/strong> form, this would be:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"183\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/12-kore-kuruma-da-1024x183.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3837\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/12-kore-kuruma-da-1024x183.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/12-kore-kuruma-da-300x54.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/12-kore-kuruma-da-768x137.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/12-kore-kuruma-da-1536x275.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/12-kore-kuruma-da-2048x366.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">This is a car. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">This is a car. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">kore wa kuruma da.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3053\u308c \u306f \u304f\u308b\u307e \u3060\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3053\u308c\u306f<ruby>\u8eca<rt>\u304f\u308b\u307e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3060\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This is in the present\/future tense, because it describes what &#8220;is&#8221; in the present. If we were to express this in the past tense, we would use &#8220;was&#8221; in English, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;deshita&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3057\u305f\u300d<\/span> in polite Japanese and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;datta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u3063\u305f\u300d<\/span> in informal Japanese.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-sidebar\">This is just a quick summary as this is really a whole other lesson in itself. In my online course, this is explained early on so you would already know all this before learning about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>. If you would like to catch up now, <a href=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/desu\/\">my article about <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span><\/a> explains the different types of words and phrases that can be used as the &#8220;verb&#8221; in Japanese.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Now let&#8217;s return to what I said earlier:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong>For nouns and na-adjectives, the present\/future tense form is connected to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span> instead of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Our informal example above has the &#8220;verb&#8221; as <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kuruma da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u8eca<rt>\u304f\u308b\u307e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3060\u300d<\/span> &#8211; that is, a noun plus <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span>. We would do the same if instead of a noun, we had a na-adjective like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;y\u016bmei&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6709\u540d<rt>\u3086\u3046\u3081\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u300d<\/span> (famous).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To connect a clause like this to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, we would change the <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span> to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span>. The result would be:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">This is a car, so&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">kore wa kuruma na node&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3053\u308c \u306f \u304f\u308b\u307e \u306a \u306e\u3067&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3053\u308c\u306f<ruby>\u8eca<rt>\u304f\u308b\u307e<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306a\u306e\u3067&#8230;<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Remember, this is the exception. <strong>For any other type of &#8220;verb&#8221;<\/strong>, such as a regular verb, an i-adjective, or even a noun or na-adjective in the negative form or past tense, we just <strong>use the regular informal form<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>For example, if our clause just used a regular verb like <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ikimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304d\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, we would attach <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will go, so&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa iku node&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3044\u304f \u306e\u3067&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u306e\u3067&#8230;<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Whatever type of clause we have, once we attach <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> to the clause describing our reason or cause, we then just finish off our sentence with the clause describing the result or effect.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>So, what about politeness?<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>With <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, the first clause is usually expressed in the informal form, even when speaking politely.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><strong>The politeness of the sentence is therefore determined by the verb at the end of the sentence.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Unlike <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, the forms of the verbs in the two clauses don&#8217;t need to match. An informal verb in the first clause, followed by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> and a second clause in the polite form would be considered a polite sentence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In fact, a sentence where we have an informal verb with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> and then a polite verb at the end is arguably more polite than if we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> with two polite verbs.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>That is to say that <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> is inherently more polite than <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> when used in this way. The difference is quite marginal, though, so it&#8217;s not worth worrying about whether you should use one or the other.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>So that we can compare them easily, let&#8217;s see our examples from earlier again, only this time using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> instead of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"node-action\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> with an action as the reason<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Recall that our first example using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> was this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\">&#8220;<em>I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day.<\/em>&#8220;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This expressed in <strong>polite<\/strong> Japanese using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> instead of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> looks like this:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/13-go-japan-node-study-japanese-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3838\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/13-go-japan-node-study-japanese-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/13-go-japan-node-study-japanese-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/13-go-japan-node-study-japanese-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/13-go-japan-node-study-japanese-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/13-go-japan-node-study-japanese-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Polite)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Polite)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa rainen, nihon ni iku node, mainichi nihongo wo benky\u014d shimasu.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093\u3001 \u306b\u307b\u3093 \u306b \u3044\u304f \u306e\u3067\u3001 \u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061 \u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054 \u3092 \u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046 \u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u6765\u5e74<rt>\u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001<ruby>\u65e5\u672c<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u306e\u3067\u3001<ruby>\u6bce\u65e5<rt>\u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby><ruby>\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Notice that the verb at the end of this sentence is in the polite form: <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;benky\u014d shimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>. That means that the whole sentence is polite, even though the verb in the first clause, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;iku&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u300d<\/span> is in the informal form.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>If we wanted to change the whole sentence to the informal form, we would simply change that last verb to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;benky\u014d suru&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u308b\u300d<\/span>, like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/14-go-japan-node-study-japanese-informal-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3839\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/14-go-japan-node-study-japanese-informal-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/14-go-japan-node-study-japanese-informal-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/14-go-japan-node-study-japanese-informal-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/14-go-japan-node-study-japanese-informal-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/14-go-japan-node-study-japanese-informal-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">I will go to Japan next year, so I will study Japanese every day. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">watashi wa rainen, nihon ni iku node, mainichi nihongo wo benky\u014d suru.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u308f\u305f\u3057 \u306f \u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093\u3001 \u306b\u307b\u3093 \u306b \u3044\u304f \u306e\u3067\u3001 \u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061 \u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054 \u3092 \u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046 \u3059\u308b\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u79c1<rt>\u308f\u305f\u3057<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f<ruby>\u6765\u5e74<rt>\u3089\u3044\u306d\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3001<ruby>\u65e5\u672c<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u306e\u3067\u3001<ruby>\u6bce\u65e5<rt>\u307e\u3044\u306b\u3061<\/rt><\/ruby><ruby>\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e<rt>\u306b\u307b\u3093\u3054<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3092<ruby>\u52c9\u5f37<rt>\u3079\u3093\u304d\u3087\u3046<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u308b\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Just like that, we can change the politeness level of the whole sentence just by changing the last verb. The verb from the first clause that connects to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> &#8211; in this case, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;iku&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u884c<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304f\u300d<\/span> &#8211; is in the informal form regardless.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"node-i-adjective\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> with an i-adjective as the reason<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>The next example we had was:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>\u201cThe pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine.\u201d<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To say this <strong>informally<\/strong> using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, we might say:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/15-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3840\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/15-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/15-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/15-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/15-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/15-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">zubon wa kitanakatta node, sentakuki ni ireta.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3 \u306f \u304d\u305f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f \u306e\u3067\u3001 \u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d \u306b \u3044\u308c\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u306f<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u306e\u3067\u3001<ruby>\u6d17\u6fef\u6a5f<rt>\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This is, of course, in the informal form because the last verb in the sentence is <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ireta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u305f\u300d<\/span>, which is the informal past tense form of <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;iremasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The first clause ends with the i-adjective, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kitanai&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3044\u300d<\/span>, in the informal past tense:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The pants were dirty. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">zubon wa kitanakatta.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3 \u306f \u304d\u305f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u306f<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Now, as we&#8217;ve said, even if we wanted to express this whole sentence in the polite form, we wouldn&#8217;t need to change <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kitanakatta&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u300d<\/span> to the polite form. We would <em>not<\/em> need to add <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;desu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3067\u3059\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>All we would need to do make this <strong>polite<\/strong> is change the last verb of the sentence to the polite form, which would give us:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/16-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-polite-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3841\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/16-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-polite-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/16-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-polite-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/16-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-polite-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/16-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-polite-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/16-pants-dirty-node-put-in-laundy-polite-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine. (Polite)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The pants were dirty, so I put them in the laundry machine. (Polite)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">zubon wa kitanakatta node, sentakuki ni iremashita.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3 \u306f \u304d\u305f\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f \u306e\u3067\u3001 \u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d \u306b \u3044\u308c\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u30ba\u30dc\u30f3\u306f<ruby>\u6c5a<rt>\u304d\u305f\u306a<\/rt><\/ruby>\u304b\u3063\u305f\u306e\u3067\u3001<ruby>\u6d17\u6fef\u6a5f<rt>\u305b\u3093\u305f\u304f\u304d<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u5165<rt>\u3044<\/rt><\/ruby>\u308c\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Just as before, the way we connect an i-adjective to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> is to just use it in the informal form. The form of the last verb then determines the politeness of the whole sentence.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"node-na-adjective\">Using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> with a na-adjective as the reason<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Our next example is one where we need to be a little bit more careful, and that&#8217;s because our &#8220;verb&#8221; in the first clause contains a na-adjective.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>As we said, that means we need to change the <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span> from a normal informal present\/future tense clause to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The sentence we had was:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"rw-indent\"><em>\u201cThe garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside.\u201d<\/em><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To express this <strong>informally<\/strong> using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, we would say:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/17-garbage-full-node-put-outside-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3842\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/17-garbage-full-node-put-outside-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/17-garbage-full-node-put-outside-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/17-garbage-full-node-put-outside-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/17-garbage-full-node-put-outside-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/17-garbage-full-node-put-outside-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside. (Informal)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai na node, soto ni dasu yo.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u306a \u306e\u3067\u3001 \u305d\u3068 \u306b \u3060\u3059 \u3088\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u306a\u306e\u3067\u3001<ruby>\u5916<rt>\u305d\u3068<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u3088\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>The word, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ippai&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u300d<\/span>, which means \u201cfull,\u201d is a na-adjective (even though it ends in <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;i&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u300d<\/span>), so if we were to just say the first part of this sentence by itself, we would say:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai da.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u3060\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u3060\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>However, here we&#8217;re connecting it to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, so we need to change the <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span> to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span>:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full, so&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai na node&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u306a \u306e\u3067&#8230;<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u306a\u306e\u3067&#8230;<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>For the second part of the sentence, we then have:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">(I) will put it outside. (Informal)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">soto ni dasu yo.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u305d\u3068 \u306b \u3060\u3059 \u3088\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\"><ruby>\u5916<rt>\u305d\u3068<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u3088\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>This is in the informal form as it uses the word <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;dasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u300d<\/span>, which is the informal form of the verb <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;dashimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>, meaning \u201cto put out\u201d or \u201cto take out.\u201d<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Since this last verb is in the informal form, that means that the whole sentence is informal.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Of course, if we want to express this sentence using <strong>polite<\/strong> Japanese, all we need to do is change that last verb, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;dasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3059\u300d<\/span>, to the polite form, <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;dashimasu&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u300d<\/span>. That would give us:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"330\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/18-garbage-full-node-put-outside-polite-1024x330.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3843\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/18-garbage-full-node-put-outside-polite-1024x330.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/18-garbage-full-node-put-outside-polite-300x97.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/18-garbage-full-node-put-outside-polite-768x248.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/18-garbage-full-node-put-outside-polite-1536x495.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/18-garbage-full-node-put-outside-polite-2048x660.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">The garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside. (Polite)<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"example\"><p class=\"english\">The garbage bin is full, so I will put it outside. (Polite)<\/p><p class=\"romaji\">gomibako wa ippai na node, soto ni dashimasu yo.<\/p><p class=\"kana\">\u3054\u307f\u3070\u3053 \u306f \u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044 \u306a \u306e\u3067\u3001 \u305d\u3068 \u306b \u3060\u3057\u307e\u3059 \u3088\u3002<\/p><p class=\"kanji\">\u3054\u307f<ruby>\u7bb1<rt>\u3070\u3053<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306f\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u306a\u306e\u3067\u3001<ruby>\u5916<rt>\u305d\u3068<\/rt><\/ruby>\u306b<ruby>\u51fa<rt>\u3060<\/rt><\/ruby>\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3088\u3002<\/p><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>Once again, we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;ippai na node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3044\u3063\u3071\u3044\u306a\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> in the first clause. The first part of the sentence is the same whether we&#8217;re speaking informally or politely.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"\/>\n\n\n\n<p>As you can see, the way we structure a sentence using <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> is very similar to when we use <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span>, but we need to treat the verb in the first clause differently, in two ways:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>The &#8220;verb&#8221; part of the sentence is usually in the informal form, even in polite sentences<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>When the first clause, when expressed by itself in the informal form, would usually end with [noun + <span class=\"ilRom\">da<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3060<\/span>] or [na-adjective + <span class=\"ilRom\">da<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3060<\/span>], we connect it to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span> by replacing <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span> with <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"key-takeaways\">Key Takeaways<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>We can join two statements (or clauses) together, where one statement is the cause or reason for the other, using the particles <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> and <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In <strong>both cases<\/strong>, the clause describing the reason or cause usually comes first, followed by <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span> or <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span>, which is then followed by the clause describing the result or effect, like so:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"220\" src=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/00-so-because-kara-node-1024x220.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3826\" srcset=\"https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/00-so-because-kara-node-1024x220.png 1024w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/00-so-because-kara-node-300x65.png 300w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/00-so-because-kara-node-768x165.png 768w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/00-so-because-kara-node-1536x330.png 1536w, https:\/\/8020japanese.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/10\/00-so-because-kara-node-2048x440.png 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>When using <strong><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;kara&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u304b\u3089\u300d<\/span><\/strong>, the main verb in each clause can be polite or informal, but they should match.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>When using <strong><span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;node&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306e\u3067\u300d<\/span><\/strong>:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>The verb in the first clause is usually in the informal form, even when speaking politely.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>In clauses that, when expressed on their own in the informal form, have a verb that consists of a [noun + <span class=\"ilRom\">da<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3060<\/span>] or [na-adjective + <span class=\"ilRom\">da<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u3060<\/span>], the <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;da&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u3060\u300d<\/span> should be changed to <span class=\"ilRom\">&#8220;na&#8221;<\/span><span class=\"ilKana hideThis\">\u300c\u306a\u300d<\/span>.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>The politeness of the sentence as a whole is determined by the politeness of the verb at the end of the sentence.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Probably the simplest way to build more complex sentences in Japanese is to take two simple sentences and join them together to form one longer sentence. Just as in English, one of the most common situations where we would do this is when we want to explain the reason for doing something or to show [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":4,"featured_media":3826,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[1],"tags":[],"class_list":["post-3812","post","type-post","status-publish","format-standard","has-post-thumbnail","hentry","category-uncategorized","post-wrapper","thrv_wrapper"],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v25.9 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>How to say &quot;so&quot; and &quot;because&quot; in Japanese - 80\/20 Japane